<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - 5 SPEED TRANSMISSIONS SPICER ES65-5 - DISASSEMBLE - INPUT
        SHAFT
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="3">
        <title>INPUT SHAFT</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">After removing the main drive gear bearing cap from the transmission, place it on a
                workbench with the open side down (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301341">Figure 41</hotlnk>). Tap the edges of the cap with a rubber mallet until the
                bearing cup falls out. Remove the shim and baffle. Normally it isn't necessary to replace the shim
                unless end play exceeds the specified .003 to .008 inch (.08 to .20mm) after reassembly.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301341" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301341" filename="../figg13/G1301341.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 41. Place Main Drive Gear Bearing Cap on Workbench</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove the main drive gear pocket bearing cup for replacement (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301342">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301342" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301342" filename="../figg13/G1301342.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 42. Remove Main Drive Gear Pocket Bearing Cup</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press the bearing off the shaft and replace it with a new one (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1301343">Figure 43</hotlnk>). It is good practice to always replace bearings during
                service.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1301343" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1301343" filename="../figg13/G1301343.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 43. Press Bearing Off Shaft</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Always wear safety glasses when pulling components off a shaft to protect your eyes from any
                        flying metal pieces.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
